[5] Pennsylvania (Indiana County)
Date: Wed 4 Dec 2019 12:28 AM EST
Source: Pittsburgh Post-Gazette [abridged, edited]
https://www.post-gazette.com/local/region/2019/12/03/State-declares-whooping-cough-outbreak-indiana-county/stories/201912030150


The state Department of Health will hold a free whooping cough vaccination clinic [Thu 5 Dec 2019] in Indiana, Pennsylvania, after a rare whooping cough outbreak spread through 4 school districts in Indiana County, infecting as many as 45 people since August [2019].

Though there was one early case in the county in early August [2019], the outbreak spread quickly in the 4 school districts, sending staff scrambling to understand what whooping cough -- also known as pertussis -- is and how it spreads.

"This was my 1st experience," said Robert Heinrich, director of education for Indiana Area School District, which has had 6 or 7 cases of the disease, including one faculty member.

Penns Manor Area and Marion Center Area school districts -- which both border Indiana Area School District -- have had whooping cough cases, too. The 4th school district is Blairsville-Saltsburg School District, which straddles both Indian and Westmoreland counties.

The free, walk-in vaccination clinic will be administering the "Tdap" vaccination shot -- for tetanus, diphtheria, and acellular pertussis -- from 2 to 6 pm [Thu 5 Dec 2019] at the Indiana County State Health Center, 75 N Main St, Indiana.

The state is encouraging anyone from 10 to 64 years old in the county to take advantage of the clinic, particularly anyone who is pregnant or works or lives with or around pregnant women or infants, who are the most susceptible to the worst effects of whooping cough.

But the vaccine's potency can fade after that without an adolescent or adult booster shot. That may be what explains the outbreak's spread in Indiana County, which has one of the highest vaccination rates in the state for the Tdap vaccine at 97.6% for kindergartners and 99% for 12th graders, but a lower 88.8 % rate for the county's 8th graders. Indiana Area's 6 or 7 cases have all been of students who had previously been vaccinated, though they may not have been vaccinated since kindergarten.

"There does appear to be a gap for students there between kindergarten and 12th grade who are headed to college," said Nate Wardle, a department of health spokesman. "That could be a sign of where this is coming from." High school senior vaccination levels may jump because they are preparing to head to colleges and universities, which require tetanus shots, which means they would probably get the whole Tdap booster then, Mr Wardle said.

How it spread across 4 school districts is still being studied, Mr Wardle said, though some of the earliest cases could have been kids at the same movie, mall, vocational technology center, or some other gathering point. "We don't have any information as to what the exact cause was yet," he said. Mr Heinrich said Indiana Area has tried to piece together what put their cases in common, too. "We couldn't find a pattern whether it was a group of wrestlers, cheerleaders, or some specific building," he said.

Mr Wardle said the last outbreak like this occurred 3 years ago, during the same time of year, with a similar number of cases, and also among school kids, in Chambersburg, Franklin County.

The district has responded to each case with letters home to all of the students' families in the buildings where the students attended -- the district has had cases in 4 of its 6 buildings so far -- providing basic information about the disease and listing a contact number for the state health department.

The district also specifically reached out to the families of students who were either immuocompromised or not yet vaccinated to warn them again of the dangers of staying unvaccinated. Though state law says in cases like this the school district may exclude unvaccinated students, the district has not yet done that.

But once a student or the one faculty member was confirmed with whooping cough, they were told to stay home at least 15 days from the onset of symptoms, or for 5 days after they began taking antibiotics, which is included in the state law, too.

The district had all of the cases closer to the beginning of the year, but has one unconfirmed case still being investigated from just last week, Mr. Heinrich said. "The state told us it's not unusual to have a few cases every now and then around the state," he said. "But this many in this area is unusual."

